  <body> <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode">🌙 Dark Mode</button>
    <h2>TEACHING STATION FRAMEWORK</h2>
    <p><i>A universal guide for conducting any examination or procedure in a
        teaching setting.</i></p>
    <!-- Phase 0: Learning Contract -->
    <!-- (Added to ensure clear objectives & tailored teaching) -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;0: Agree the Learning Agenda</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>0. Clarify Objectives &amp; Baseline</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Establish Learner Needs:</b> Ask the student what parts of the
          skill they feel least confident about.</li>
        <li><b>Set Specific Outcomes:</b> "By the end of this session you should
          be able to list the steps, demonstrate safe technique, and explain
          positive/negative findings."</li>
        <li><b>Check Prior Experience:</b> "Have you practised this on
          mannequins or patients before?"</li>
        <li><b>Identify Preferred Learning Style / Accessibility Needs:</b>
          Visual, hands‑on, verbal, etc.</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <!-- Phase 1: Pre-Procedure Protocol -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;1: Pre‑Procedure Protocol (The Setup)</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>Wear gloves when talking!</strong></summary>
      <ul>

        <li><b>Introduce yourself:</b></li>

        <li><b>Greet the Patient:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Use a warm, professional greeting</li>
          <li>Make eye contact and smile</li>
          <li>Ensure the patient is comfortable</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Self-Introduction:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>State your full name</li>
          <li>Mention your role (e.g., "I'm Dr. Smith, a senior doctor")</li>
          <li>Wear your ID badge visibly</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Introduce the Student:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Use the student's full name</li>
          <li>State their level of training (e.g., "third-year medical student")</li>
          <li>Explain their role in the session</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Verify Patient Identity:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Ask for full name and date of birth</li>
          <li>Check against medical records if available</li>
          <li>Confirm any allergies if relevant</li>
        </ul>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>Wear gloves when explaining!</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Explain the Indication:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>(e.g., "To better understand your abdominal pain, we need to
            perform an examination of your tummy.").</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Explain the Procedure:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>Clearly .....terms. Mention what the patient will feel (e.g., "I
            will be gently pressing on different parts of your abdomen. It
            shouldn't be painful, but please let me know if you feel any
            discomfort.").</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Check Contraindications:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>(Clinician to self/student) "</li>
          <li>recent surgery </li>
          <li>specific conditions to be aware of?"</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Gain Verbal Consent:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>explicitly (e.g., "Are you happy for us to proceed with the
            examination?").</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- Added pointer: Signpost objectives to patient & student -->
        <li><b>Signpost Session Objective:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>"We'll first demonstrate the technique, then answer any questions
            before practice."</li>
        </ul>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>3. Preparation &amp; Positioning</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Offer a Chaperone:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Always offer a chaperone for intimate examinations</li>
          <li>Use clear language: "Would you like a chaperone present?"</li>
          <li>Document the offer and patient's response</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Ensure Adequate Exposure:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Explain what clothing needs adjustment</li>
          <li>Provide gowns or drapes as needed</li>
          <li>Ensure privacy throughout the examination</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Position the Patient:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Instruct clearly: "Please lie flat on your back"</li>
          <li>Check comfort: "Is this position okay for you?"</li>
          <li>Adjust bed/chair height as needed</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Check for Pain or Discomfort:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Ask about current pain levels</li>
          <li>Note any movement restrictions</li>
          <li>Make necessary accommodations</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Perform Hand Hygiene &amp; PPE:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Wash hands in front of the patient</li>
          <li>Don appropriate gloves/apron/mask</li>
          <li>Explain the reason for PPE</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Gather &amp; Check Equipment:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Prepare all necessary instruments</li>
          <li>Check equipment function (e.g., stethoscope, torch)</li>
          <li>Ensure clean and single-use items are available</li>
        </ul>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <!-- Phase 2: The Core Task -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;2: The Core Procedure / Examination</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>4. Perform the Core Task</strong></summary>
      <p><i>(This is where the specific steps of the examination or procedure
          are performed. The instructor may demonstrate first, then allow the
          student to perform under supervision.)</i></p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Common Examination Types:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Cardiovascular Examination</li>
          <li>Respiratory Examination</li>
          <li>Abdominal Examination</li>
          <li>Neurological Examination</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Demonstration Phase:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Instructor performs the entire sequence first</li>
          <li>Verbalize each step clearly</li>
          <li>Explain key anatomical landmarks</li>
          <li>State the rationale for each action</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Systematic Approach:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Inspect: Look before touching</li>
          <li>Palpate: Feel for abnormalities</li>
          <li>Percuss: Assess underlying structures</li>
          <li>Auscultate: Listen for sounds</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Patient Comfort & Safety:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Use minimal necessary pressure</li>
          <li>Warn before any potentially uncomfortable steps</li>
          <li>Check in frequently: "How are you doing?"</li>
          <li>Watch for non-verbal signs of discomfort</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Teaching Points:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Highlight normal vs. abnormal findings</li>
          <li>Explain clinical significance</li>
          <li>Relate to underlying anatomy/physiology</li>
          <li>Demonstrate proper technique</li>
        </ul>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <!-- Phase 3: Instructional Dialogue -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;3: Instructional Dialogue (For the Student)</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>5. Explain &amp; Teach</strong></summary>
      <p><i>(This dialogue occurs between the instructor and the student, while
          always maintaining respect for the patient.)</i></p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Demonstration of Technique:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Show proper instrument handling</li>
          <li>Demonstrate correct body mechanics</li>
          <li>Highlight common mistakes to avoid</li>
          <li>Explain the rationale behind each movement</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Explanation of Findings:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Describe normal findings clearly</li>
          <li>Identify and explain any abnormalities</li>
          <li>Use appropriate medical terminology</li>
          <li>Relate findings to underlying anatomy</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Questioning Strategy:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Ask open-ended questions</li>
          <li>Use "what if" scenarios</li>
          <li>Encourage critical thinking</li>
          <li>Check understanding at each step</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Skill Refinement:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Provide specific, actionable feedback</li>
          <li>Demonstrate corrections</li>
          <li>Allow repeated practice</li>
          <li>Praise progress and effort</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Teach-Back Method:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Ask students to explain in their own words</li>
          <li>Have them demonstrate back the technique</li>
          <li>Correct any misunderstandings</li>
          <li>Reinforce correct practices</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Reflective Practice:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Ask about challenges faced</li>
          <li>Discuss what went well</li>
          <li>Identify areas for improvement</li>
          <li>Set goals for next session</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Documentation Guidance:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Show how to record findings</li>
          <li>Explain medical terminology</li>
          <li>Highlight important details to include</li>
          <li>Discuss legal requirements</li>
        </ul>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <!-- Phase 4: Post-Procedure Protocol -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;4: Post‑Procedure Protocol (The Wrap‑Up)</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>6. Conclusion &amp; Closure</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Patient Appreciation:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Express gratitude for their participation</li>
          <li>Acknowledge their contribution to learning</li>
          <li>Offer contact information for follow-up</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Patient Comfort & Dignity:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Assist with dressing if needed</li>
          <li>Ensure they're comfortable</li>
          <li>Offer water or assistance if required</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Findings Summary:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Provide clear, jargon-free explanation</li>
          <li>Highlight normal findings</li>
          <li>Explain next steps if further tests needed</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Address Concerns:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Ask patient for questions</li>
          <li>Verify understanding</li>
          <li>Provide written information if needed</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Student Development Plan:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Schedule practice sessions</li>
          <li>Arrange follow-up assessments</li>
          <li>Set specific learning objectives</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Constructive Feedback:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Highlight strengths observed</li>
          <li>Identify areas for improvement</li>
          <li>Provide specific examples</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Learning Resources:</b></li>
        <ul>
          <li>Recommend reading materials</li>
          <li>Share relevant guidelines</li>
          <li>Suggest online resources</li>
        </ul>
      </ul>
    </details>
